  "output": "This is a pure Python codebase (async job-scraper + SQLite store, `agent.py`/`fetchers.py`/`store.py`/`filters.py`/`models.py`/`pipeline.py`/`notify.py`, ~1900 LOC) — there's no React/JS anywhere, so that checklist item doesn't apply. Here's what I found in the areas that do apply.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, in a loop, for every job fetched in a run:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nBoards like Microsoft/Amazon/Google routinely return hundreds to thousands of listings per run, so this is hundreds/thousands of round-trip queries plus individual `INSERT`/`UPDATE` statements, each with its own SQLite planning overhead. Fix: one batched `SELECT ... WHERE key IN (...)` to build a lookup dict, then `executemany` for inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's variable limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            touched.append(job.key)\n\n    cur.executemany(\"INSERT ... ON CONFLICT(key) DO UPDATE SET ...\", [...])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in touched])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n(Simplest path: switch `_insert`/`_update` to a single `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT(key) DO UPDATE` and drop the separate branches — one `executemany` instead of three query shapes.)\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job — `filters.py:11-27`\n\n`_compile()` builds fresh `re.Pattern` objects from `include`/`exclude` word lists, but it's called *inside* `match()`, which runs once per job:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFor N jobs and K keywords, that's N×K regex compiles when it should be K. Fix: compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re, ...)]\n```\n\nand change `match()` to consume pre-compiled lists instead of raw strings.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `Job.to_row()` deep-copies the discarded `raw` payload — `models.py:71-75`\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # deep-copies every field, including `raw`\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then immediately throws that copy away\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict` recursively deep-copies nested dict fields — including `raw`, which can hold the entire source JSON blob (Apple/Meta/Workday payloads aren't small). That copy is wasted work since it's popped a line later. `to_row()` runs on every new/changed job in `Store._insert`/`_update`. Fix: build the row dict manually instead of going through `asdict`:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company, \"external_id\": self.external_id,\n        \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url, \"location\": self.location,\n        \"department\": self.department, \"employment_type\": self.employment_type,\n        \"posted_at\": self.posted_at, \"salary_range\": self.salary_range,\n        \"key\": self.key, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\n## 4. Caching opportunity — `Job.content_hash` recomputed multiple times per job\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` (sha256 over 4 fields), not memoized. In `store.diff()` it's read once for the comparison (`store.py:67`) and then implicitly recomputed inside `to_row()` when `_insert`/`_update` runs (`models.py:75`) — 2 hashes per touched job. Minor on its own, but free to fix: since `Job` is `@dataclass(slots=True)`, `functools.cached_property` won't work directly (no `__dict__`), so either add an explicit slot for the cache or just compute the hash once in `diff()` and pass it through rather than recomputing inside `to_row()`.\n\n## 5. Memory retention — `raw` payload kept on every `Job` for the whole run\n\nEvery parser attaches `raw=j` (the full source JSON) to each `Job` (`fetchers.py`, e.g. lines 97, 117, 146, 513...). These objects are held in memory across `fetch_all` → `filter_jobs` → `store.diff`, and `raw` is stripped only at the very end in `to_row()`. It's never read anywhere in between (not in `filters.py`, not in `notify.py` — `notify_webhook` also calls `to_row()`, stripping it too). For a full multi-source run (Microsoft/Amazon/Google/Apple can each return hundreds to thousands of listings), that's a lot of retained JSON with no consumer. Not a leak (it's GC'd when the process exits after `pipeline.run()`), but if the DUMP_LIMIT-style workflows in `agent.py` ever get extended to hold jobs longer or run as a long-lived service, this would matter. If `raw` isn't used for debugging/inspection anywhere downstream, consider dropping it right after fetch/parse rather than carrying it through the whole pipeline.\n\n## 6. Sequential pagination (correctness-preserving, so a soft suggestion only)\n\nFetchers like `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix` (fetchers.py:969-979, 1021-1031, 1083-1092) `await` each page strictly in sequence because the loop's exit condition depends on the previous page's `seen` set / fresh-count being empty. This is correct and avoids over-fetching, so I wouldn't change the core loop — but a few of these APIs return a `total`/`count` on page 1 (e.g. `fetch_phenom` already uses `total`, `fetch_bytedance` uses `data.count`). For those, you could fetch page 1, compute the known remaining page count, and fire the rest concurrently (bounded by the existing `concurrency` semaphore) instead of one-at-a-time — meaningful latency win for boards with 20-40 pages. Not worth doing for fetchers that must page until an empty response (no known total).\n\n## Not applicable here\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend in this repo.\n- **Classic web-app N+1 via ORM lazy-loading**: N/A, no ORM — but the same pattern exists in raw SQL form (finding #1).\n- **Memory leaks in the traditional sense**: this is a short-lived CLI process (`pipeline.run()` runs once and exits); no persistent server loop, so nothing accumulates across \"requests.\" `Store` connections and `httpx.AsyncClient`s are properly closed via `with`/`try-finally` (`pipeline.py:42`, `fetchers.py:1142-1146`).\n\n**Priority order**: fix #1 (N+1 SQL) first — it's the one with real, run-scaling cost. #2 is a quick, safe win. #3/#4 are small but free. #5/#6 are situational.\n",
